Okay, I put up the new nesting box today. This is how it looks at its new location in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one asks: "What exactly is in there?"
I have one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR LED, which I extracted from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the unusual shape of this plastic box is the pivoting side wall of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no power in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I haven't photographed the cell or the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging on the side of the nesting box is the battery.
If it's fully charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
I'd call that a feature. So birds also get some private space.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be enough for this setup. The old access points I replaced last fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
It's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and arrange it downwards in the garden.
Maybe I'll do that, when/if I set up further nesting boxes with cameras. I probably need that in areas that are further away from the house.
The camera is offline now and I don't know why. It simply shut down one hour after sunset.
Maybe the battery didn't continue to charge three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or less than half a day was too little to fully charge the battery.
I'll probably have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
I think a few more sensors would be a good thing in general.
And maybe a battery that can at least theoretically keep this thing running overnight.
Oh, and another lens.
Fisheye is pretty overdone.
